g.text: Notes:· 1.Devices stream data into IoT Hub gateway, via MQTT/AMQP/HTTPS. These devices are not managed through Azure.· 2.Azure-managed edge devices stream data into IoT Hub via the IoT Edge hub. Management of these devices is via Azure IoT Hub device management services.· 3.Onboarding of new edge devices may be accomplished via Azure Device Provisioning Service.· 4.Event Hubs may be used with IoT Hub to allow enhanced routing (e.g. bifurcation of raw device data to separate schema-matched topics).· 5.ESP may subscribe to IoT Hub or Event Hub using the new Event Hub SDK-based connector.· 6.Hot path for data – these services should be event-based (e.g. Event Hub, Service Bus, Event Grid) or otherwise real-time· 7.Warm path for data – e.g. database-based services, which may be queried in near real-time · 8.Cold path for data – data that is infrequently read. Blob storage and data lake.· 9.ETL process to load data at-rest into CAS in-memory tables.· 10.Analytic models created through Model Studio (or other clients).· 11.Analytic models are versioned in Model Manager for deployment.· 12. Analytic models are referenced from the model repo in ESP Studio.· 13.Deployment-ready ESP projects are loaded into Event Stream Manager.· 14.Future state – edge deployments managed by Event Stream Manager via IoT Hub APIs.· 15. IoT Hub routes telemetry data to blob storage or ADLS for cold storage.· 16.Logic Apps publish enrichment data into Event Hub.· 17.Azure Functions read and output to Event Hub.
